Mulberry for Debian
====================

This package provides Mulberry, a traditional desktop email and calendar
client with support for IMAP4, CalDAV, CardDAV, and related standards.

Debian-Specific Information
---------------------------

### Installation Paths

The Debian package installs files to the following locations:

  * Binary: /usr/bin/mulberry
  * Resources and plugins: /usr/lib/mulberry/
  * Documentation: /usr/share/doc/mulberry/
  * Desktop integration: /usr/share/applications/mulberry.desktop
  * Icon: /usr/share/pixmaps/mulberry.xpm

### User Configuration

Mulberry stores user configuration and data in:

  * Preferences: ~/.mulberry/preferences.mbp
  * Local mailboxes: ~/Mail/ (default)
  * Local address books: ~/AddressBooks/ (default)

### Desktop Integration

Mulberry is registered as a handler for:

  * mailto: URLs (email addresses in web browsers, documents, etc.)
  * webcal: URLs (calendar subscriptions)
  * message/rfc822 MIME type (email message files)

To make Mulberry your default email client in most desktop environments,
use your system's default applications settings (e.g., System Settings >
Default Applications in KDE, Settings > Default Applications in GNOME).

### SSL/TLS and S/MIME Certificates

Mulberry includes its own certificate management system for SSL/TLS and
S/MIME encryption. Certificates are stored in your profile directory:

  * CA certificates: ~/.mulberry/Certificates/Authorities/
  * Accepted servers: ~/.mulberry/Certificates/Servers/
  * User S/MIME certificates: ~/.mulberry/Certificates/Users/
  * Personal S/MIME certificates: ~/.mulberry/Certificates/Personal/

For SSL/TLS connections, Mulberry uses both system CA certificates and
its own certificate store. The application will prompt you to accept or
reject certificates that cannot be verified. Accepted certificates are
stored in the Servers directory for future connections.

To add a trusted CA certificate, use Mulberry's certificate import
dialog (accessible through the application's security preferences) rather
than modifying the certificate directories manually

### Kerberos/GSSAPI Authentication

Kerberos (GSSAPI) authentication support is available through the GSSAPI
plugin. Ensure you have configured Kerberos credentials (kinit) before
attempting to use GSSAPI authentication.

### Known Issues and Limitations

Mulberry is mature software with development that appears to have
largely stalled:

  * No OAuth2 support for modern email providers (Gmail, Office365, etc.)
  * Some modern email features may not be supported
  * Upstream development appears very limited since ~2011-2012
  * Consider modern alternatives (Thunderbird, Evolution) for new deployments

### Reporting Bugs

For bugs in the Debian packaging or build, please file issues at:
https://github.com/yitzhaq/mulberry-main/issues

For issues with Mulberry itself, community support may be available
through the GitHub repository. Note that upstream development appears
to be very limited.

